<dl id="n54113g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54113g">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54113g"> 113(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bow of shower <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54113g"><li>FW 228.09 </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/lexkb.htm#n54113g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/kb/l39kb.htm#n54113g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54113g">MS BL 47477-277</ms> </li><li>JJA 51:405 <a name="kad9" href="../../ff/fdra/kda.htm#kbd7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/kb/kbd7.htm#n54113g">Draft: II.1&sect;2.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Swaran is defeated. Fingal learns that Ryno, his youngest son, is slain. He laments his death and hears the story of Lamderg and Gelchossa.]</font> Terrible were their forms in battle; but calm was Ryno in the days of peace. He was like <mark>the bow of the shower</mark> <font color="green">[rainbow]</font> seen far distant on the stream; when the sun is setting on Mora; when silence dwells on the hill of deer. <small> James MacPherson, <a name="JMPO2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JMPO2"><cite title="source">The Poems of Ossian</cite></a> (1806), Vol. II, <font size="-1">FINGAL</font> Book V, 85</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
